-- Atlas, BHP, Lend Lease, Telstra, Santos, Woodside: Australia Stock Preview
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-04-27T21:59:23Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-27/atlas-bhp-lend-lease-telstra-santos-woodside-australia-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of
companies whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. The
preview includes news announced after markets shut yesterday
unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index futures contract expiring in June
slumped 1.8 percent to 4,794 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The
S&P/ASX 200 Index was little changed at 4,880. The Bank of New
York Australia ADR Index lost 4.2 percent.  
 Mining stocks: Copper fell the most in 10 months, leading a
slide by industrial metals, after cuts in credit ratings for
Greece and Portugal. Copper futures for July delivery plummeted
4.7 percent to $3.3825 a pound on the Comex in New York.  
 BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, gained 0.1 percent to A$42. Its American depositary
receipts slumped 4.4 percent in New York. Rio Tinto Group (RIO
AU) dipped 0.1 percent to A$76.40 in Sydney.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil fell to the lowest level in more
than a week in New York.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd. (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, rose 0.3 percent to A$46.45.
Santos Ltd. (STO AU), the third largest, advanced 0.3 percent to
A$13.87.  
 Gold producers: Gold futures rose to the highest price in
two weeks in New York on demand for an alternative to holding
currencies. Newcrest Mining Ltd. (NCM AU), Australia’s largest
gold producer, gained 0.9 percent to A$34.52.  
 Atlas Iron Ltd. (AGO AU): The iron-ore producer will sell
about A$65 million of shares to help fund expansion, including
an upgrade of its Pardoo mine and development of a new project
at Wodgina, the Australian Financial Review reported, citing an
unnamed source. The shares fell 1.8 percent to A$2.69 when they
last traded on April 23.  
 Lend Lease Group (LLC AU): Australia’s largest developer
was raised to “buy” from “neutral” at UBS AG. The shares
lost 2 percent to A$8.63.  
 Telstra Corp. (TLS AU): Australia’s biggest telephone
company may cut as many as 900 jobs from its operations division
in the next financial year, the Australian Financial Review
reported, citing union official Len Cooper. The shares gained
0.3 percent to A$3.20.  
 West Australian Newspapers Holdings Ltd. (WAN AU): The
publisher was downgraded to “sell” from “neutral” at UBS.
Its shares dropped 2.2 percent to A$8.04.  
